Emu Roll

by: Jessie Shen

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game, because I always enjoy playing the dinosaur game when there isn't a Wi-Fi connection available nearby. It inspired me to make Emu Roll, and add more changes to my game, including three lives per play, the heads falling from the sky, and be able to move, to make my game more fun.

2. What I Learned

I learned how to improve my game, so that the player would have more fun in avoiding/dodging the heads. I incorporated all the feedback I received from my teachers and classmates, including being able to change the direction that the emu is facing, being able to see the score at the top of the screen, and spawning the heads faster, so that at one point, the player (emu) will die, and be able to replay to reach a personal high score.

3. Architecture of My Game

In Emu Roll, there are three states; a menu state, a game state, and an end state. In the menu state, there is the option to view the instructions, or to go right into the game. In the game state, all the action of the game happens. In the end state, it tells the player the score, and the option to play again. I have six classes in my game, including a GamePanel class, an ObjectManager, a GameObject class, a head spawning class, an emu class, and an EmuRoll class. The Emu and the head spawning class both extend the GameObject class. The ObjectManager controls the spawning heads, and checks the collision.

4. Technical Implementation

I restricted the emu from going off of the screen when moving left, right, and when jumping. Additionally, I used two different variables for the heads that spawn; the rolling heads, and the falling heads. I changed part of my code so that the time between each spawn of the head would get shorter. I am proud of making my emu be able to jump, because I had to think back about previous recipes that included a velocity variable.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of creating my game was coming up with small ideas that would change my game to look more appealing. This included creating my own background, making the cloud move, and including the three pixel hearts that kept track of the lives the player had left. I faced these difficulties by looking at other games, which inspired me to add more detail.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

If I was to continue working on my game, I would want to make different levels in my game, including an easy, medium, and hard level, so that the heads would spawn a lot faster the higher the level, and also be able to buy power-ups/upgrades to help the emu.
